<DOC><DOCNO> AP881015-0036 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0507EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Corruption     10-15 0161</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Corruption,0163</SECOND><HEAD>Major Chinese Corporation Trimmed in Anti-Corruption Drive</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government ordered a major Chinesecorporation linked to official corruption to consolidate and severties with a welfare fund headed by the son of senior leader DengXiaoping, an official report said today.   The state-run investment and development firm, Kang HuaDevelopment Corp., is reported to be a main target of a governmentcampaign against the pervasive problem of official corruption. Thecorporation says it controls about 200 companies nationwide.   The People's Daily newspaper said Deng singled out the companyfor criticism. It said he ordered it to cut ties with the ChinaWelfare Fund for the Handicapped, which is run by his disabled son,Deng Pufang.   Unconfirmed reports in the Hong Kong press have said Kang Huaofficials used links to the welfare fund to obtain tax privilegesand extra import permits. Reports have charged that the company hasprofiteered in imports and other hard-to-get materials.</TEXT></DOC>